  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight by characterizing the properties of the discovered failures (called LAPSUS) and correlating them with the structure of the input voice commands. Specifically, in the case study, the authors analyze the generated LAPSUS for two real-world vApps and conclude that vApps with long and complex installation names are more vulnerable to their fuzzing-generated attacks than those with short, simple names. This analysis links failure susceptibility to a property of the input (the invocation name's length and complexity) and provides a concrete mitigation strategy for developers (use simple, unique names). However, it does not perform a deeper diagnostic analysis to explain *why* the underlying Intent Classifier model fails on these inputs, such as linking the failures to specific training data biases, spurious features, or other model-internal vulnerabilities. The analysis characterizes the failures without explaining the root cause within the model itself.",
